<subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-a-circle">
    <title>Area of a circle</title>

    <introduction>
        
        <p>
        It is calculated using the formula <m> \textbf{A} = \pi r^2 </m> 
        where <m>\pi = \frac{22}{7}</m> or <m>3.142</m> and 
        <m> r  \,\text{is the radius of the circle} </m>. It is measured in square units.
        </p>

    </introduction>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-calculating-the-area-of-a-circle-in-different-situations">
        <title>Calculating the area of a circle in different situations.</title>
        <activity>
            <p>
                <m> \textbf{What you require:}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                A ruler, pieces of strings and pieces of sticks or chalks.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            On the ground, Mark a point using a piece of stick and lable it O.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Tie a stick with each end of the string and fix one stick on the ground at point O.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf{(a)}</m> Stretch the string and draw a circle as shown on the right.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf{(b)}</m> Draw several other circles using different lengths of strings.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                          <m>\textbf{(a)}</m> Measure the radius of each circle that you have drawn.  
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf{(b)}</m> Using formula, <m>\textbf{area}= \pi r^2</m>, calculate the area of each circle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw circles in your exersise book and work out the area of each.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your work with other learners in your class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway:}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Area of a circle of radius <m>(r)</m> is given by: <me>A=\pi r^2</me>.
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the area of a circle whose area is <m>14 \, \text{cm}</m> use <m>\pi = \frac{22}{7}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Area of a circle}= \pi r^2</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Area} =\amp \frac{22}{7} \times 14 \times 14 </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 616 \, cm^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>

        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                   Find the area of each of the following circles with 
                   O as the centre use <m>\pi = \frac{22}{7}</m>: 
                </p>
                <sidebyside>
                    <image width="40%">
                    <latex-image label="Circle1">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                           % Draw the circle with a very thick pink outline
                            \draw[very thick, black] (0,0) circle (2cm);

                            % Draw the diameter
                            \draw[thick, magenta] (-2,0) -- (2,0);
                            
                            % Mark the center
                            \fill[magenta] (0,0) circle (2pt);

                            % Label the diameter
                            \node at (0,0.3) {\textbf{42 cm}};
                            \node at (0,-0.3) {\textbf{0}};
                            \node[anchor=north, scale=1.2] at (0,3) {\textbf{(a)}};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                        
                    </image>
                    <image width="40%">
                    <latex-image label="Circle2">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Draw the circle
                            \filldraw[fill=white, draw=purple, thick] (0,0) circle (3);
                            
                            % Draw the radius
                            \draw[thick, magenta] (0,0) -- (3,0);
                            
                            % Draw the center point
                            \filldraw[magenta] (0,0) circle (3pt);
                            
                            % Label the radius
                            \node[anchor=south, black] at (1,0) {\textbf{\large $3.5 \,cm$}};
                            
                            % Label the area formula
                            \node[anchor=north, scale=1.2] at (0,-0.3) {\textbf{0}};
                            \node[anchor=north, scale=1.2] at (0,4) {\textbf{(b)}};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                       
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{(a)}</m> <m>\text{Area} = \pi r^2</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    We are given;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Diametter} =\amp 42 \,cm</mrow>
                        <mrow> \text{Radius(r)}= \amp \frac{42}{2} </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 21 \,cm</mrow>

                    </md> 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>Area= \amp \frac{22}{7} \times 21 \times 21 </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp \frac{22}{7} \times 21^2 </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 1\,386 \,cm^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The area of <m>\textbf{(a)}= {\color{blue}1\,386 \,cm^2}</m>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{(b)}</m> <m>\text{Area} = \pi r^2</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    We are given;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\text{Radius(r)}= 3.5\,cm</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Area}=\amp \frac{22}{7} \times 3.5 \times 3.5 </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{22}{7} \times 3.5^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 38.5 \, cm^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                 <p>
                    The area of <m>\textbf{(b)}= {\color{blue}38.5 \, cm^2}.</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        

        
    </subsubsection>




    
</subsection>